<TITLE> Markets close lower </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 27 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks ended downbeat on the opening day of the week after gaining Thursday with investors putting banks at the back end of trading and showing increased interest in state run-oil entrants. Shares of Jamuna Oil and Meghna Petroleum rose for the first time after the start of their trading on the bourses. Market observers termed the change of trading behaviour "portfolio reshaping". "It seems that the investors are changing their trend of doing business; they are now opting for shares in mutual funds, power and oil companies," said Salahuddin Ahmed, chief executive of Dhaka Stock Exchange. Sunday's trading was paced by shares in power, mutual funds and state-run oil companies, with prices of power shares going up. Some of the heavyweights in the banking sector saw their share prices increase after the sector ended lower for the last couple of days. The prime bourse kicked off its day with a rise in the general index, but it started to fall after the second hour before recovering losses in the midday sessions. It, however, declined again towards the end to close lower. The benchmark DGEN or general index was down 3.56 points, or 0.12 percent, to end at 2882.87. The DSI or all share price index closed at 2429.06, down 4.07 points, or 0.16 percent. The blue chip DSE-20 slumped 20.95 points, or 0.89 percent, to end at 2310.84. Turnover also fell to Tk 1.13 billion from Thursday's Tk 2.67 billion from trading of 10,678,042 shares. Of the traded issues 99 gained, 125 lost and some 16 remained unchanged. Grameen Mutual Fund One topped the turnover board, closing 6.25 percent higher at Tk 96.80. Jamuna Oil followed it to end at Tk 367.70, up 3.22 percent. Summit Power gained 2.99 percent to close at Tk 1505.75. Power Grid Company of Bangladesh continued its rise from Thursday to end at Tk 672.75, up 2 percent. Meghna Petroleum also rose 3.56 percent to Tk 363.10. Among the other scrips on the turnover board, BRAC Bank and AIMS 1st Mutual Fund also advanced. IFIC Bank, AB Bank and Square Pharma, however, lost. The day's major gainers were Perfume Chemicals, BCIL , M Hossain Garments, Maq Paper and Tulip Dairy. People's Insurance, Bangladesh Finance and Investment Company, BOC Bangladesh, Delta Life Insurance and Padma Oil Company emerged as the major losers. All indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended lower, with all the sectors closing mixed. Food & allied, ICT and cement shares suffered the largest losses while mutual funds, ceramics and energy issues gained the most. The CSCX or selective categories index slumped 11.84 points, or 0.24 percent, to 4745. 51. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7387.23, down 21.13 points, or 0.28 percent. The blue chip CSE-30 index declined 38.75 points, or 0.58 percent lower, to end at 6590.94. Turnover on the port city's bourse fell to Tk 161.332 million, which Thursday was Tk 277.312 million, from 1,715,410 traded shares. Losers outnumbered gainers 70 to 39 with seven issues holding steady. bdn
